metadata.name: Sub Section Patina #799
metadata.description:
"Sub Section Patina" is inspired by street art and the marks and layering from that art form. If you zoom in on a small section of a wall that artists have marked, sprayed paint, and plastered with posters, some beautiful effects start to happen.

While the "Sub Section Patina" layers are building up, there is a tendency to destroy the layers below. The layering is similar to a wall many street artists have contributed. Sometimes just a section will be covered and filled with something else. Sometimes large areas of the canvas are covered up. Other layers will be put on top of one another, creating a new chaotic image. 

Features:
Four different sizes: 9x16, 11x14", 12x18", 12x12"
Portrait or landscape orientation
~500 color pallets, one black and white, one cyan, magenta, yellow and black, and the rest from Jam3/nice-color-palettes.

Dependencies:
processing/p5.js
lodash/lodash
Jam3/nice-color-palettes
substack/point-in-polygon

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: Puppet #21
metadata.description:
We are all immersed in our lives. A life in which we are actually puppets of fate.
We are overwhelmed with work and problems in the prison we have created for ourselves.
While beauty is right under our feet and we cannot see it.
In this work, each mannequin is a symbol of a human surrounded in a room. The elements of the room include chandeliers and windows...
Each room is hung from the ceiling by a string that represents a puppet in the hands of fate.

Hope you enjoy

metadata.name: Sweeping #138
metadata.description:
Sweeping is a piece in which I explore the uses of noise fields. Using them in the most cliche way possible, but trying to make something unique out of that.

What started out as an innocent weekend project grew out to be quite the piece, which is why I am publishing it here.



Sweeping uses the GPU of your machine for its shading, which means it won't run particularly well on mobile devices. My recommended way of viewing this piece is on a PC with a dedicated GPU.

---

- Double Click to open a User Interface
- In the UI, you can toggle the paper texture and export

---

Made with p5js + webgl by Wouter Missler, 2022.

metadata.name: Spradow #36
metadata.description:
A girl ventured into a dark jungle and encountered spiders. As she tried to leave, the hills and woods seemed to move and block her escape. She became trapped in the jungle, and despite search efforts by others, she was never found. Legend has it that her cries can still be heard in the village for over thousands of years.

Pressing the “i” key will invert the colors of the artwork, allowing you to see it in negative mode. Use this feature to explore new perspectives on this already stunning piece. If you want to save your favorite iterations of the artwork, press S to save your current image as a high-resolution file. Alternatively, pressing T allows you to save just the transparent layer so that you can superimpose it onto other images or backgrounds easily.
